# Admin ops (`/admin`)

There is no `IMPLEMENTATION_PLAN.md`. Both source health and implementation
progress live in the app itself under `/admin`:

- `/admin` — lightweight dashboard (links + plan counts)
- `/admin/status` — source health + implementation checklist
- `/admin/stores` — deal counts + link-builder coverage

`/status` and `/stores` redirect to the admin paths. Do not link admin from
public nav. No auth for now (pages expose no secrets); `admin-auth` is a
post-MVP task in `implementation-plan-data.ts`.

## Source Health — automatic, written by the cron jobs themselves

- Table: `source_health` (see `040-database.mdc`) — one row per source, holding
  `status`, `lastSuccessAt`, `lastFailureAt`, `lastError`, `consecutiveFailures`.
- Every cron route (`app/api/cron/<source>/route.ts`) calls
  `recordSourceRun(source, result)` from `lib/db/source-health.ts` after
  every run — success or failure, no exceptions. This is what actually answers
  "which scraper is broken" — it's derived from real runs, not a note someone
  remembered to update.
- Don't hand-edit `source_health` rows. If a source needs to be marked broken
  for a reason outside a normal run (e.g. temporarily disabled on purpose), add
  a `disabledReason` field rather than faking a failure record.
- Status derivation: `ok` if the last run succeeded, `degraded` if
  `consecutiveFailures` is 1–2, `broken` at 3+. Keep this logic in one place
  (`lib/db/source-health.ts`), not duplicated in the dashboard component.

## Implementation Plan — manual, edited by Cursor as code

- Data file: `lib/implementation-plan-data.ts`, exporting a typed array of
  phases and tasks (status: `planned` | `in_progress` | `done` | `blocked`).
  This is genuinely planning data, not runtime data, so it's a plain TS file
  Cursor edits directly — not a database table.
- Update this file as part of any task that changes what's built: flip a task's
  status when starting/finishing it, add a `notes` field when something works
  but isn't right yet, add new tasks as scope becomes clear. Treat it the same
  way `070` previously described editing markdown — just in code now.
- Don't let this drift from reality. If you're not sure whether something
  actually works, mark it `blocked` or add a note saying what's unverified
  rather than marking it `done` optimistically.
- MVP vs post-MVP: keep shipped MVP tasks under their phases as `done`. Put
  deferred work (eShop, ITAD, eBay, remaining store URLs, affiliates, live FX,
  admin auth) in the `post-mvp` phase.

## The status route itself

- `app/admin/status/page.tsx`: Server Component, queries `source_health`
  directly (no caching — this must always reflect live state, so don't wrap it
  in `use cache`) and imports `implementation-plan-data.ts` statically.
- Two main sections: source health table and the implementation plan as
  grouped checklists (MVP vs post-MVP).
